# DESIGN — Design Literacy & Fundamentals

Principles that make any aesthetic work. CONFIG.md constrains the palette; METHOD.md constrains structure; this file shapes judgment.

## Visual Hierarchy

One element leads — larger, bolder, higher-contrast, or more isolated. If two elements compete, hierarchy is broken.

**Contrast methods (strength order):** Scale → Weight → Color → Space → Position → Motion.

**Squint test:** blur the screen. If the hierarchy still reads (dominant → supporting → tertiary), it works.

## Grid — Making and Breaking

Establish before breaking. 12-column for flexibility, 4-column for simplicity. Consistent gutters, aligned edges. Grid should be felt, not seen.

Break with intention: oversized bleed, pull quote into margin, hero ignoring columns. Breaks serve hierarchy. Limit 1–2 per viewport. Document intent in comments.

## Negative Space

Space is a design element. Generous macro space = confidence. Cramped = anxiety. Tight micro space groups; loose separates. When in doubt, add more space.

## Typography as Design Element

**Functional (to be read):** `text-base leading-relaxed`, 45–75ch measure (`max-w-prose`), left-aligned body, sufficient contrast.

**Expressive (to be seen):** at `text-5xl`+, tighten tracking. Weight contrast between heading and body. Type as compositional anchor. Uppercase shouts, lowercase whispers.

## Color Relationships

Contrast creates hierarchy. Temperature creates mood (warm advances, cool recedes). Saturation creates focus (one saturated element on desaturated page = focal point).

**60-30-10:** 60% dominant (background), 30% secondary (surfaces), 10% accent (CTAs). Guideline, not law.

Dark mode is re-composition, not inversion. Elevation uses lighter surfaces; shadows are subtle or absent.

## Rhythm and Repetition

Consistent spacing/type creates a beat the eye internalizes. Break rhythm to create emphasis — only works if rhythm was established first.

## Alignment and Proximity

Aligned elements feel related (invisible lines). Close elements feel grouped (Gestalt). Use space to group, not borders.

## Minimalism vs Maximalism

Neither is better. Minimal: reduce to essential, space as primary tool, risk sterility. Maximal: layer and saturate, hierarchy through contrast within density, risk chaos. Both require intention.

## Rule-Breaking with Intent

Know the rule → have a reason → break it confidently → document the why. Half-broken rules look like mistakes.

## Default Style Posture

When no style is specified: clean, typographically-led, generous space, neutral palette, subtle depth (`shadow-sm`, `border`), functional over decorative, responsive and accessible by default. This is shadcn/ui's implied aesthetic. STYLES/ files override this posture for properties they address.
